tOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epelvi-ureteric junction\u003C/strong\u003E (PUJ) is the most common site of renal calculus obstruction due to its natural anatomical narrowing where the renal pelvis transitions into the ureter. Other potential sites of obstruction include the \u003Cstrong\u003Epelvic brim\u003C/strong\u003E where the ureter crosses the iliac vessels, the \u003Cstrong\u003Ebladder wall\u003C/strong\u003E at the vesicoureteric junction, and within the \u003Cstrong\u003Emajor\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eminor calyces\u003C/strong\u003E of the kidney.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe PUJ represents a physiological narrowing and change in direction of urinary flow, making it particularly susceptible to stone lodgement. Understanding these anatomical points of narrowing is crucial for predicting where stones are likely to become trapped.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pelvi-ureteric junction is the most common site of renal calculus obstruction due to its natural anatomical narrowing.","Anatomical narrowings in the urinary tract are prime locations for stone obstruction, with the pelvi-ureteric junction being the most frequent site."],"references":["Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","ISO 690Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Fontenelle LF, Sarti TD. Kidney Stones: Treatment and Prevention. Am Fam Physician. 2019 Apr 15;99(8):490-496. PMID: 30990297","Peerapen P, Thongboonkerd V. Kidney Stone Prevention. Adv Nutr. 2023 May;14(3):555-569. doi: 10.1016/j.advnut.2023.03.002. Epub 2023 Mar 9. PMID: 36906146; PMCID: PMC10201681"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49844"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15019"}},"stemMedia":{